AGI -&nbsp;The Codacons filed an appeal to the Tar of Lazio on drinking water, bringing before the judges the question of the most widespread equipment in Italy for water filtration and treatment, and asking the administrative tribunal to cancel the acts of the Ministry of Health.
<br In recent years it has been recorded in Italian houses and public exercises such as restaurants a growing spread of devices intended for the treatment of water aimed at human consumption - explains the Codacons - Treatments that do not aim to make drinking a water that is not already morphologically, but to allow changes in the organoleptic characteristics, that is to "cool" the waters for domestic uses. The Ministry of Health, by decree of 7 February 2012, n. 25 containing "Technical provisions concerning equipment for the treatment of water intended for human consumption" aims to "ensure that treatments do not prejudge the quality of water >, already suitable for health purposes, that the treatment equipment ensures the stated effects and that the complete information on the effects of treatment is adequately supplied to the consumer", but does not provide specific controls by the health authorities.
The legislation in force reduces to a mere burden of the manufacturer/distributor the conformity of the device intended for the treatment of water for human use, thus replacing the control by the competent health authorities', such as impartial bodies and with greater guarantees on the quality of the product intended for consumers.
<br The use of water treatment equipment can also have repercussions on the health front: depending on the techniques used, it can reduce or even eliminate minerals > such as calcium and/or magnesium (in reverse osmosis technique), as well as &nbsp; on the contrary, involve an increase in sodium (especially in the ion exchange filtering technique) strongly advised, for preventive purposes, for the whole population (and in particular for those suffering from diseases such as diabetes, hypertension etc.) - the Coda still explains. Not only. The commercialization of treated water must be supported by a complete information (especially regarding the composition of water, the treatments applied and its effects) in order to prevent the user from being misled and/or confused in his choice and fail to consider that the same c.d. "treated water"> may be similar or even better or healthier than mineral water, as they seem to suggest some claims used to advertise such products, without scientific indications on the quality and characteristics of water. The latter will have to highlight the Antitrust in the light of the possible misleadingness of the messages addressed to the public.
&nbsp;
For these reasons Codacons, in the light of the new scenario determined in Italy following the diffusion of apparatuses for the treatment of water intended for human consumption, asked Tar to cancel the decree 25/2012 of the Ministry of Health, which does not provide specific controls by the competent health authorities on the treated and/or filtered waters used in commerce.&nbsp;

